<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-10-09T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-10-09T00:00:00-05:00" n="685" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d685">
                                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.00111 Armament
                                    Control/141</note>
                                <head>
                                    <hi rend="italic">The Chief of Naval Operations</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Standley</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                            State</gloss>
                                    </hi>
                                </head>
                                <opener>
                                    <seg rendition="#left">(SC)A 14–6</seg>
                                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                                        <placeName>
                                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-10-09">October 9,
                                            1935</date>.</dateline>
                                </opener>
                                <p>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: The following dispatch, received
                                    this date from the Naval Attaché of the United States Embassy in
                                    Rome, is quoted for your information: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                        <p>“Request the following information relative to
                                            President’s Proclamation: May visit and search of
                                            American merchant vessels be carried on on the high seas
                                            by either belligerent? As a state of war has been
                                            proclaimed may rights under laws of war be
                                            exercised?”</p>
                                    </quote>
                                </p>
                                <p>It is requested that this department be advised as to the nature
                                    of the reply to be made to this dispatch.</p>
                                <closer>
                                    <signed>W. H. <hi rend="smallcaps">Standley</hi>
                                    </signed>
                                </closer>
                            </div>
                            </body></text></TEI>